(appendix
  :book                "Book of Narrative Games"
  :letter              "C"
  :title               "The Body Language Catalog"
  :dialect             "motoi"
  :audience            :kid
  :also-for            :adult
  :content-rating      :G
  :training-eligible   #t
  :confidentiality     "public"
  :book-version        "1.0.0"
  :prose
"Every part-verb, its intent, its signature parameters, and a one-line
example. This is the reference kids will keep open while writing
scenes.

If a character does not use at least three of these verbs in a scene,
they are furniture. That is the rule of thumb this catalog exists to
enforce.

---

## Ambient — always running

**(part/breathe entity rate)** — the rise-and-fall of the torso.
Never stops for a live character. Rate is in Hz (cycles per second).

- 0.15-0.20 — meditative, ominous, dying (villain, monk, elder)
- 0.22-0.30 — calm adult (Mira, father, most NPCs)
- 0.35-0.45 — child, excited adult
- 0.55-0.80 — panic, exertion, fear

Example: `(part/breathe mira 0.28)` — Mira breathes at a calm-adult
rate.

**(part/sway entity amount)** — small ambient side-to-side drift.
Amount is pixels of drift. 0 is unnatural — only for villains or
statues. 1 is barely visible; 2-3 is normal; 4-6 is nervous or
uncertain.

Example: `(part/sway kid 3)` — the kid fidgets slightly.

---

## Head — direction and attention

**(part/tilt entity degrees)** — head tilts to one side. Positive is
right (from viewer's perspective); negative is left. Signals
curiosity, confusion, considered listening.

- 0 — neutral
- 5-8 — mild curiosity
- 10-15 — puzzled, considering
- 20+ — cartoonish; usually too much

Example: `(part/tilt mira 8)` — Mira tilts, curious.

**(part/turn entity direction)** — full body/head turn. Direction is
a symbol: `'front` `'back` `'left` `'right`. Sprite must have the
corresponding view or engine substitutes.

Example: `(part/turn father 'left)` — father turns to face Mira.

**(part/look-toward entity x y)** — eyes track to a specific pixel
coordinate. Head may follow if the position is far enough off.

Example: `(part/look-toward mira 200 300)` — Mira looks at the point
where the player character stands.

**(part/nod entity)** — two quick head-down-then-up motions. Signals
agreement or acknowledgment. Duration is fixed (about 30 frames).

Example: `(part/nod mira)` — Mira nods agreement.

---

## Torso and posture

**(part/lean entity px)** — body leans forward (positive) or back
(negative). Signals interest (forward) or withdrawal (back).

- 0 — neutral upright
- 3-6 — mild interest or withdrawal
- 8-12 — clear engagement or recoil
- 15+ — extreme; usually too much

Example: `(part/lean father -6)` — father leans back on hearing news.

**(part/bow entity depth)** — a bow of the given depth (pixels of
head drop). Signals respect, apology, formal greeting.

Example: `(part/bow monk 20)` — a deep respectful bow.

---

## Arms and hands

**(part/wave entity hand)** — a wave. Hand is `'left` or `'right`.
Signals greeting, farewell, attention-getting.

Example: `(part/wave mira 'right)` — Mira waves hello.

**(part/reach entity x y)** — arm extends toward a screen position.
Signals grasping, offering, pointing-with-hand.

Example: `(part/reach mira 300 200)` — Mira reaches for something at
(300, 200).

**(part/point entity x y)** — one arm extends with index finger to
the position. More specific than reach.

Example: `(part/point mira 400 200)` — Mira points at the door.

**(part/shrug entity)** — both shoulders rise briefly. Signals 'I
don't know' or 'not my business.' Duration fixed (about 20 frames).

Example: `(part/shrug shopkeeper)` — shopkeeper shrugs when asked
something outside her knowledge.

---

## Legs and movement

**(part/step entity direction)** — a single step in the given
direction. Signals approach or retreat. Direction is `'forward`
`'back` `'left` `'right`.

Example: `(part/step villain 'forward)` — villain takes one deliberate
step toward the player.

**(part/twist entity degrees)** — torso rotates while feet stay.
Signals evasion, dodging, sudden alertness.

Example: `(part/twist kid 30)` — the kid twists away from a slap.

---

## Face

**(part/expression entity emotion)** — sets the facial expression.
Emotion is a symbol from a small vocabulary:

- `'neutral` — no expression (default)
- `'smile` — warm smile
- `'soft-smile` — small closed-mouth smile
- `'small-smile` — barely-there smile (villain's one and only)
- `'grin` — wide showing-teeth
- `'sad` — corners of mouth down
- `'angry` — brows down, mouth tight
- `'thinking` — brows slightly furrowed
- `'surprised` — eyes wide, mouth slight-open
- `'held-back-tears` — eyes glisten, mouth tight
- `'small-cry` — one tear
- `'closed-eyes` — eyes shut (in memory, in sleep, in grief)

Example: `(part/expression mira 'soft-smile)` — Mira smiles quietly.

---

## Raise and lower

**(part/raise entity thing)** — raises a specific thing. Thing can be
`'head` `'arm-left` `'arm-right` `'both-arms` `'hand-left`
`'hand-right` `'brow`. Complementary to `part/lower`.

Example: `(part/raise mira 'brow)` — Mira raises an eyebrow.

**(part/lower entity thing)** — same options as raise, but lowers.

Example: `(part/lower kid 'head)` — the kid drops his head.

---

## Halt

**(part/halt entity)** — stops all ambient motion from this entity —
breath, sway, everything. Character becomes statue-still. Use for
shock beats, dramatic pauses, one-cycle held breath.

Example: `(part/halt father)` — father freezes on hearing news.

To restart, call the ambient verbs again:

```scheme
(part/halt father)              ;; freeze
(world/after 60
  (lambda () (part/breathe father 0.22)))  ;; unfreeze
```

---

## Composition rules

Multiple part-verbs on one character in one frame COMPOSE. Breath +
tilt + sway all run simultaneously. The engine layers them.

```scheme
;; Mira, sitting, breathing, tilted, swaying, looking at player.
(entity/pose! mira 'sitting)
(part/breathe mira 0.28)
(part/tilt mira 8)
(part/sway mira 2)
(part/look-toward mira 200 300)
```

Five verbs, one composed animation. She sits, breathes, has her head
tilted, sways a little, and looks at you. That is a live character.

Do not repeatedly call the same verb every frame. Set it once; the
engine keeps it running. `on-frame` callbacks that call
`(part/breathe mira 0.28)` sixty times per second waste cycles.

---

## Twelve character-signature templates

Copy these into your game. Tune parameters.

```scheme
;; The calm elder (grandmother, monk, sage).
(define (signature/calm-elder ent)
  (part/breathe ent 0.18)
  (part/sway    ent 1))

;; The friendly adult (Mira, shopkeeper).
(define (signature/friendly-adult ent)
  (part/breathe ent 0.28)
  (part/sway    ent 2))

;; The excited child.
(define (signature/child ent)
  (part/breathe ent 0.45)
  (part/sway    ent 3))

;; The nervous first-timer.
(define (signature/nervous ent)
  (part/breathe ent 0.55)
  (part/sway    ent 5))

;; The gruff artisan (blacksmith, carpenter).
(define (signature/gruff-artisan ent)
  (part/breathe ent 0.24)
  (part/sway    ent 1))

;; The dying / very ill.
(define (signature/dying ent)
  (part/breathe ent 0.10)
  (part/sway    ent 0))

;; The villain.
(define (signature/villain ent)
  (part/breathe ent 0.13)
  (part/sway    ent 0))

;; The animal (cat).
(define (signature/cat ent)
  (part/breathe ent 0.35)
  (part/sway    ent 1))

;; The animal (dog).
(define (signature/dog ent)
  (part/breathe ent 0.42)
  (part/sway    ent 2))

;; The animal (horse).
(define (signature/horse ent)
  (part/breathe ent 0.20)
  (part/sway    ent 1))

;; The ghost / spirit.
(define (signature/ghost ent)
  (part/breathe ent 0.05)          ;; almost none
  (part/sway    ent 3))             ;; but drifts

;; The bureaucrat / customs officer.
(define (signature/formal ent)
  (part/breathe ent 0.25)
  (part/sway    ent 0))             ;; stiff
```

Twelve templates. Enough to cover 90% of characters you'll write.

---

## A test — draw a scene with only body language

Try to write a 30-second scene where nobody speaks but a story
happens. Use ten part-verbs across two characters. See if a friend
can tell you what happened.

If they can, you have mastered body language.

If they can't, watch your scene again with the volume off. Notice
what moved when. Notice what stayed still. Rewrite.

---

## Summary

Twelve ambient/pose/gesture verbs. Twelve signature templates.
Composition-friendly. Set-and-forget. Multiple verbs simultaneously
on one entity layer into one composed animation.

Every character in your game breathes. Every character in your game
uses at least three verbs per scene. That is the rule this appendix
exists to teach.")
